<br>
Next to him, on the rough-hewn stone steps of the Bazaar, deep within the heart of Luclin, soft white hands peeked out of emerald robes, providing a rock of support. Granite hair wrapped around knife-like ears, shifting slightly as the Koada’Dal’s chiseled countenance looked down at the broken warrior.<br>
<br>
“You are sure? If so, this must be the work of the followers of Bertoxxulous,” the elf said, his voice a harsh, wavering whisper. “It is hard to retain one’s perspective in dark times such as these.”<br>
<br>
“I believe so, my…” Paroxysms of coughing wracked the gnome’s body as a black ichor shot from his lips, trying to flee the host it had tortured. As it struck the floor, the stone sizzled in protest. Pausing to gather his strength, he continued. “My friend, it is time for me to go. I will find a quite place to die. Please,” he hissed through pressed lips, “know that the time I spent with you and Society were the brightest times of my life.” Like pistons, his arms shot out, catching the dirt and pushing him up and out of Illudin’s arms.<br>
<br>
A single crystalline tear formed in the eye of the Koada’Dal; it broke free, crawling down his cheek. The magus stood slowly, snapping his eyelids shut to regain his composure. Slowly, like a sleepwalker, Illudin raised his hand to a salute. “May our stories cross in another world, brother Cykl. You will not be forgotten.” As the gnome limped away, his left leg freezing under a creeping chill of paralysis, the elf slipped down to the ground, shimmering tears of ice dripping to the cold earth.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Why has this happened? What would possess one to sow such destruction indiscriminately? It was my fault for not seeing the signs, for expecting honor from the worshippers of disease and destruction,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> he pondered while awaiting teleportation to the Greater Faydark and what passed for home, despite those blasted, conspiratorial &quot;Anti-Mage&quot; priests. Coldly, he berated himself. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  My ideals have failed. The Society is collapsing around me, Ironscale has vanished – taken by his Empire as a traitor, I suspect – and the young ones are being poisoned and driven mad. I must atone.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> He tilted his head slightly, looking out, as a sadistic smile crept across his face and the crimson glimmer of madness crossed his crystal blue eyes. “Yes. I know what I must do. The orcs in Crushbone, tonight, will share my agony. I will torture their minds and break their ranks, until they experience exquisite pain.” Lips closed, a grating, disconcerting chuckle erupted from his throat. “Tonight, Emperor Crush will have no legions to support. His rivers will flow with blood to slake my thirst for vengeance.”<br>
<br>
Switching one of his steins for a massive hammer he wrested from the hands of a dying forest giant, he erupted in raucous, maniacal laughter. “Tonight, tonight, tonight – the orcs die! Die! They will serve me, and slaughter their own kind. Servitors of evil will taste my wrath and drink deep of its beautiful agony. Those who stand in my way will be crushed!”<br>
<br>
With that, the Society was broken, and its founder, the Arbitrator, stepped into a personal twilight.<br>
